{"questionId":"11908","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A set of data comprises of five numbers&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{x_{1\\,}}{\\text{,}}\\,\\,{x_2}{\\text{,}}\\,\\,{x_3}{\\text{,}}\\,\\,{x_4}{\\text{,}}\\,\\,{x_5}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mrow>\n        <mn>1</mn>\n        <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      </mrow>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>,</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>,</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>3</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>,</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>,</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;which have been placed in ascending order.&nbsp;</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence, show that a data set with only 5 numbers in it cannot have any outliers.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"UQ + 1.5IQR = 1.25{x_4} + 1.25{x_5} - 0.75{x_1} - 0.75{x_2} \\geqslant {x_5}\">\n  <mi>U</mi>\n  <mi>Q</mi>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1.5</mn>\n  <mi>I</mi>\n  <mi>Q</mi>\n  <mi>R</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>⩾</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>Since&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"1.25{x_4} + 0.25{x_5} \\geqslant 0.75{x_1} + 0.75{x_2}\">\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>0.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>⩾</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;due to the ascending order.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>Similarly&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"LQ - 1.5IQR = 1.25{x_1} + 1.25{x_2} - 0.75{x_4} - 0.75{x_5} \\leqslant {x_1}\">\n  <mi>L</mi>\n  <mi>Q</mi>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>1.5</mn>\n  <mi>I</mi>\n  <mi>Q</mi>\n  <mi>R</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>⩽</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>Since&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"0.25{x_1} + 1.25{x_2} \\leqslant 0.75{x_3} + 0.75{x_4}\">\n  <mn>0.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>⩽</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>3</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;due to the ascending order.</p>\n<p>So there are no outliers for a data set of 5 numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"11908","referenceCode":"EXM.1.SL.TZ0.5b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Hence, show that a data set with only 5 numbers in it cannot have any outliers.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.1—Concepts, reliability and sampling techniques"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}